antibody responses, presumably by the induction of long-lived

519
00:32:03.334 --> 00:32:04.504
antibody responses.

520
00:32:05.314 --> 00:32:08.664
So how does this do that? Why do they make such potent antibody responses?

521
00:32:09.504 --> 00:32:12.344
And we think it's all have to do with structure.

522
00:32:12.364 --> 00:32:16.334
And it's quite ironic that at the time we initially developed these VLPs, and

523
00:32:16.384 --> 00:32:20.284
we did this so we could generate good conformational dependent epitopes

524
00:32:20.364 --> 00:32:22.904
on the surface. There was this paper that came out from

525
00:32:23.744 --> 00:32:27.504
Bachmann and Zinkernagel that hypothesized that B cells

526
00:32:27.524 --> 00:32:31.084
specifically recognize antigens with repetitive

527
00:32:31.164 --> 00:32:35.144
epitope spacing of 50 to 100 angstroms. And why did they think that?

528
00:32:35.524 --> 00:32:38.724
It's because this spacing is unique to microbial

529
00:32:38.764 --> 00:32:42.644
surfaces like the outer shell of a virus or bacterial pili,

530
00:32:43.154 --> 00:32:46.644
and protein complexes of this spacing are just not

531
00:32:46.724 --> 00:32:50.204
seen on the vertebrate animal surfaces that are exposed to

532
00:32:50.284 --> 00:32:54.164
systemic immunity. And so I like to think of the B cell receptors

533
00:32:54.204 --> 00:32:57.684
as essentially have being evolved as an antigen-specific

534
00:32:58.084 --> 00:32:59.584
pattern recognition receptor.

535
00:33:00.804 --> 00:33:04.144
So what we think is happening here is that when these multivalent

536
00:33:04.304 --> 00:33:08.184
antigens interact with the B cell receptors on the surface of cells,

537
00:33:08.864 --> 00:33:12.184
it forms a oligomerization of the downstream signaling

538
00:33:12.194 --> 00:33:12.924
molecules,

539
00:33:13.984 --> 00:33:17.284
an exclusion of inhibitory molecules that send very strong

540
00:33:17.344 --> 00:33:21.264
signals to generate high antibody responses that last a

541
00:33:21.304 --> 00:33:24.934
long time, as opposed to monomeric antigens, which are the type that are

542
00:33:24.944 --> 00:33:28.724
normally floating around in our body, which tend to induce low

543
00:33:28.804 --> 00:33:30.624
antibody levels of short duration.

544
00:33:31.404 --> 00:33:33.464
So now let's turn into the virology.

545
00:33:33.774 --> 00:33:37.404
And I really think that, and we didn't know any of this initially, the

546
00:33:37.444 --> 00:33:41.044
virologic features of how this virus infects has as much to do with this

547
00:33:41.084 --> 00:33:45.044
success as does the ability to induce such high

548
00:33:45.104 --> 00:33:48.744
levels of antibodies. So we developed a mouse cervical

549
00:33:48.804 --> 00:33:52.304
vaginal challenge, based upon some what we call HPV

550
00:33:52.324 --> 00:33:56.264
pseudoviruses, where they encapsidate a marker plasmid rather than

551
00:33:56.304 --> 00:33:59.644
the genome. And what we found is that this process is

552
00:33:59.664 --> 00:34:03.444
remarkably slow, the slowest process for any virus that we've

553
00:34:03.484 --> 00:34:07.084
ever seen. And so surprisingly, when we infected the

554
00:34:07.144 --> 00:34:09.424
vaginal tract, the virus didn't bind anything.

555
00:34:10.284 --> 00:34:11.344
Okay? It didn't bind

556
00:34:12.444 --> 00:34:15.944
the cervical squamous or even columnar epithelial

557
00:34:16.044 --> 00:34:19.725
cells. But if we traumatized the epithelium, it

558
00:34:19.824 --> 00:34:21.944
very avidly bound the basement membrane.

559
00:34:22.513 --> 00:34:26.484
And what we found is what it's binding on the basement membrane is heparan sulfate

560
00:34:26.504 --> 00:34:30.324
proteoglycans. But they have specific modifications

561
00:34:30.745 --> 00:34:34.584
which aren't found on the surface of epithelial cells or actually

562
00:34:34.644 --> 00:34:36.924
any other cells that we've tested in the body.

563
00:34:37.475 --> 00:34:41.245
They have a lot of HSPGs, but they don't have the specific modifications

564
00:34:41.584 --> 00:34:45.265
that are required for binding. And this binding induces a series of

565
00:34:45.324 --> 00:34:48.964
conformational changes, quite complex, that eventually

566
00:34:49.104 --> 00:34:52.665
exposes a receptor surface on the

567
00:34:53.423 --> 00:34:56.324
virus that can now bind the cell surface receptor.

568
00:34:56.924 --> 00:35:00.884
And again, it's such a slow process, and so it allows for a long time for these

569
00:35:00.984 --> 00:35:03.604
antibodies to collect and prevent infection.

570
00:35:05.004 --> 00:35:08.484
And the other thing it does is it provides a more efficient way for the

571
00:35:08.564 --> 00:35:11.154
antibodies to get to the site of infection.

572
00:35:11.784 --> 00:35:15.704
Initially, we thought that this vaccine could potentially work because there

573
00:35:15.724 --> 00:35:18.824
is a substantial amount of transudation of IgG

574
00:35:19.704 --> 00:35:23.694
through the neonatal Fc receptor in the vaginal tract,

575
00:35:23.784 --> 00:35:26.674
more than in most mucosal surfaces.

576
00:35:26.684 --> 00:35:30.524
But when we looked in the cervical vaginal mucosa of

577
00:35:30.664 --> 00:35:34.364
vaccinated women, what we found is that the levels were about 10 times

578
00:35:34.424 --> 00:35:34.784
lower

579
00:35:35.724 --> 00:35:37.844
through most of the cycle than they were in the serum.

580
00:35:38.104 --> 00:35:42.064
And at the time of ovulation, the vaccine-specific antibodies and all

581
00:35:42.144 --> 00:35:43.984
antibodies dropped another tenfold.

582
00:35:44.384 --> 00:35:48.264
So we were concerned that these lower level of antibodies wouldn't be sufficient to

583
00:35:48.284 --> 00:35:52.064
produce long-term protection from infection, which in fact what the

584
00:35:52.104 --> 00:35:52.984
vaccine does.

585
00:35:53.804 --> 00:35:57.424
But then when you think about that it has to infect from a wounded

586
00:35:57.504 --> 00:36:01.334
site, this allows direct exudation of interstitial

587
00:36:01.424 --> 00:36:05.154
antibodies that are also going to ooze out at the site of wounding.

588
00:36:06.164 --> 00:36:10.004
And it's been recently shown, quite surprisingly, that interstitial antibody

589
00:36:10.044 --> 00:36:12.404
levels are similar to those in blood.

590
00:36:12.844 --> 00:36:16.704
So by the time the virus reaches its binding site on the basement membrane,

591
00:36:17.004 --> 00:36:17.564
it's actually

592
00:36:19.004 --> 00:36:22.404
exposed to virtually the same antibodies as if it would be

593
00:36:22.444 --> 00:36:23.984
circulating in the blood.

594
00:36:25.524 --> 00:36:28.944
So one of the things we asked then is how much antibody is needed for

595
00:36:28.964 --> 00:36:29.564
protection?

596
00:36:30.644 --> 00:36:34.584
And we couldn't do this in the clinical trials because there are so few

597
00:36:34.644 --> 00:36:37.604
breakthrough infections, and there's no immune correlates with

598
00:36:37.644 --> 00:36:41.628
breakthroughs.And so we turned to our mouse model, and we

599
00:36:41.748 --> 00:36:45.528
asked, are the plateau levels after vaccination near

600
00:36:45.768 --> 00:36:47.328
the minimum needed for protection?

601
00:36:47.888 --> 00:36:51.208
And will the four-fold difference, I forgot to mention this, there's only a four to

602
00:36:51.308 --> 00:36:55.148
two-fold difference between three doses and one dose

603
00:36:55.508 --> 00:36:57.488
if you go out to 10 or 15 years.

604
00:36:59.728 --> 00:37:03.608
And so what we did is we did a classic passive transfer experiment where

605
00:37:03.648 --> 00:37:06.688
we vaccinated a rabbit, in this case, three times

606
00:37:06.748 --> 00:37:10.508
with our VLPs, and then we diluted the serum

607
00:37:10.628 --> 00:37:14.288
and transferred it into a naive mouse that hadn't been

608
00:37:14.348 --> 00:37:18.168
vaccinated and then challenged that animal

609
00:37:18.248 --> 00:37:22.128
intravaginally with HPV pseudoviruses that express luciferase.

610
00:37:22.498 --> 00:37:25.608
And so if you get signal, you're getting infections. If you don't, you don't.

611
00:37:26.737 --> 00:37:30.468
And so what we found is that you could actually dilute the sera that would be

612
00:37:30.528 --> 00:37:34.228
circulating in that mouse, could be 10,000-fold lower than what was

613
00:37:34.288 --> 00:37:38.128
circulating in that rabbit and still get strong protection, which is

614
00:37:38.138 --> 00:37:42.008
totally amazing. And then so we asked the question, well, what's the

615
00:37:42.068 --> 00:37:42.708
mechanism of

616
00:37:43.588 --> 00:37:47.208
infection inhibition if you have what we call a high dose, which is only

617
00:37:47.288 --> 00:37:49.708
100-fold dilution versus a low dose?

618
00:37:50.448 --> 00:37:53.858
And what we found is that at a high dose, it's basically happening like you see in

619
00:37:53.888 --> 00:37:57.768
an in vitro neutralization assay, where the

620
00:37:57.808 --> 00:38:01.468
virus, it gets coated with antibodies and can't interact with these

621
00:38:01.648 --> 00:38:05.568
HSPGs. But surprisingly, at low dose, what we

622
00:38:05.648 --> 00:38:07.958
see is that we actually see basement membrane binding.

623
00:38:08.508 --> 00:38:12.028
We see evidence of this conformational change, but we never see the

624
00:38:13.128 --> 00:38:16.648
virus to be stably associated with the cell surface.

625
00:38:17.188 --> 00:38:21.108
Instead, we see it predominantly attached to monocytes

626
00:38:21.128 --> 00:38:25.068
and neutrophils. So we think that these

627
00:38:25.188 --> 00:38:28.348
relatively low levels of antibodies serve as handlebars for

628
00:38:28.388 --> 00:38:31.728
phagocytosis by the neutrophils

629
00:38:32.148 --> 00:38:35.908
and/or there's possible that it could be causing degranulation after they

630
00:38:35.948 --> 00:38:36.728
bind the cells.

631
00:38:38.788 --> 00:38:42.088
So explanations for the high potency of VLP vaccines.

632
00:38:42.828 --> 00:38:44.848
We think, again, there are two critical factors.

633
00:38:44.968 --> 00:38:47.088
First of all, structure, structure, structure.

634
00:38:47.538 --> 00:38:51.348
The dense repetitive display of neutralizing epitopes on the

635
00:38:51.408 --> 00:38:55.368
surface of the VLPs makes them exceptional inducers of high

636
00:38:55.448 --> 00:38:57.388
titer and durable antibody responses.

637
00:38:57.868 --> 00:39:00.408
And then it's the mechanism of HPV infection.

638
00:39:00.828 --> 00:39:03.248
This is why other STD vaccines don't work.

639
00:39:03.768 --> 00:39:04.308
They don't have

640
00:39:05.248 --> 00:39:08.268
the ability to be neutralized by such low levels of antibodies.

641
00:39:08.868 --> 00:39:11.428
The remarkable slow infection process in vivo,

642
00:39:12.148 --> 00:39:15.968
with an obligate initiation at an acellular

643
00:39:16.048 --> 00:39:19.768
site, it's the only virus that initiates infection at an acellular site,

644
00:39:20.208 --> 00:39:24.088
makes the virus exceptionally susceptible to inhibition by low levels of

645
00:39:24.148 --> 00:39:24.788
antibodies.

646
00:39:26.408 --> 00:39:30.268
And so now in the last few minutes, I'm just going to turn to tell you

647
00:39:30.328 --> 00:39:33.808
that the VLPs can do more than prevent HPV infection.

648
00:39:34.308 --> 00:39:38.168
We think that they can actually become guided missiles to be

649
00:39:38.188 --> 00:39:42.008
used in therapy. This is an example of where if you do some

650
00:39:42.028 --> 00:39:45.328
basic research, you may find something interesting that has

651
00:39:45.368 --> 00:39:49.108
translational implication. And what we found, again, surprisingly,

652
00:39:49.608 --> 00:39:52.968
is I told you that the virus normally binds specially modified

653
00:39:53.568 --> 00:39:56.808
forms of HSPGs and the basement membrane.

654
00:39:56.838 --> 00:40:00.628
Well, it turns out that almost all cancer cells develop the same

655
00:40:00.668 --> 00:40:01.968
type of modifications.

656
00:40:02.788 --> 00:40:03.928
Okay? And

657
00:40:05.168 --> 00:40:09.088
so what this does is, again, we can think about the VLPs

658
00:40:09.188 --> 00:40:12.988
as a platform to serve as a guided missile to treat

659
00:40:13.048 --> 00:40:16.958
cancer. And so a company, Oro Bioscience, started up by

660
00:40:16.958 --> 00:40:20.888
Eli de los Pinos, the CEO, to exploit this

661
00:40:20.928 --> 00:40:24.598
technology. And we've worked together for more than 10 years where we do most of

662
00:40:24.608 --> 00:40:28.288
the preclinical work in our laboratory, and the company does what

663
00:40:28.328 --> 00:40:31.608
companies do best, GMP production and clinical trials.

664
00:40:32.768 --> 00:40:35.778
And just to convince you that these tend to bind cancers pretty well and

665
00:40:37.108 --> 00:40:41.028
diversely, this is a panel of 129 cell lines we looked at

666
00:40:41.068 --> 00:40:44.988
for binding, and almost all bind reasonably well

667
00:40:45.128 --> 00:40:46.468
and are infected

668
00:40:47.288 --> 00:40:50.998
by HPV pseudoviruses. The one exception is hematopoietic

669
00:40:51.048 --> 00:40:54.428
cells, which are known to be low in HSPGs.

670
00:40:56.547 --> 00:40:58.648
And so we're asked the question, well, it's kind of weird.

671
00:40:58.728 --> 00:41:02.528
Why do all these cancers develop these HSPG modifications?

672
00:41:03.048 --> 00:41:05.598
And so we looked at the screen, we screened the

673
00:41:07.268 --> 00:41:11.178
RNA-seq data from these cell lines and asked what correlates with

674
00:41:11.268 --> 00:41:11.748
binding.

675
00:41:12.908 --> 00:41:16.588
And it turns out what stood out more than anything else is EMT

676
00:41:16.668 --> 00:41:20.208
transition, epithelial to mesenchymal transition,

677
00:41:20.808 --> 00:41:24.437
and that at least in our epithelial lines we looked at is driven by

678
00:41:24.468 --> 00:41:25.408
TGF-beta.

679
00:41:28.368 --> 00:41:31.728
And so what we think is happening is that these HSPG

680
00:41:31.788 --> 00:41:35.748
modifications are involved in signaling that allow

681
00:41:35.848 --> 00:41:39.788
dedifferentiation of cells. So when we get this EMT transition,

682
00:41:39.828 --> 00:41:43.068
they don't go all the way from going from epithelial cells to fibroblasts, they

683
00:41:43.128 --> 00:41:45.648
stop in the middle in an undifferentiated state.

684
00:41:46.128 --> 00:41:49.898
And we think that one of the main signaling mechanisms we've stumbled upon is

685
00:41:49.928 --> 00:41:52.308
these HSPG

686
00:41:54.308 --> 00:41:56.948
alterations that are responsible for that.

687
00:41:57.968 --> 00:42:01.928
So then the question was, well, what kind of cytotoxic payload should

688
00:42:02.008 --> 00:42:02.568
we deliver?

689
00:42:03.468 --> 00:42:07.268
And we ended up doing something by making a

690
00:42:07.328 --> 00:42:11.288
conjugate with something called IR700, which is a dye

691
00:42:11.328 --> 00:42:12.328
that's activated

692
00:42:13.288 --> 00:42:16.488
by infrared light. We can get about 200 of these

693
00:42:16.568 --> 00:42:18.968
molecules linked to the virus-like particles.

694
00:42:19.678 --> 00:42:23.648
And what's great about this is it's got dual specificity because it only

695
00:42:23.728 --> 00:42:26.688
kills when the particles are bound

696
00:42:27.428 --> 00:42:31.208
to the membrane, and it only kills when you shine the

697
00:42:31.268 --> 00:42:35.228
light. So there's basically no off-target

698
00:42:35.528 --> 00:42:36.968
killing by this drug.

699
00:42:38.128 --> 00:42:41.896
OopsAnd

700
00:42:42.136 --> 00:42:45.476
it also, we found out, has a dual mechanism of activity.

701
00:42:45.996 --> 00:42:49.876
One is we get this direct cytotoxicity, and within minutes these

702
00:42:49.916 --> 00:42:53.846
cells die because you poke these holes in the membrane due to ROS production and

703
00:42:53.896 --> 00:42:55.516
maybe mechanical stress.

704
00:42:56.476 --> 00:42:57.016
And then

705
00:42:58.036 --> 00:43:01.496
in addition to this direct necrotic type of death,

706
00:43:02.016 --> 00:43:05.936
this releases neoantigens and

707
00:43:06.096 --> 00:43:09.996
danger-associated molecular patterns, which then activate

708
00:43:10.036 --> 00:43:13.775
neoantigen T cells, and we get secondary T cell responses.

709
00:43:15.416 --> 00:43:15.556
So,

710
00:43:16.436 --> 00:43:19.716
one of the problems with this technology is because it's going to be used for so

711
00:43:19.776 --> 00:43:23.646
many different cancer types, what do you start with?

712
00:43:24.176 --> 00:43:27.716
And we started to go with kind of an orphan disease, which was

713
00:43:27.836 --> 00:43:31.776
small ocular melanomas, which form in the choroid space.

714
00:43:32.306 --> 00:43:36.156
And we initially did a Phase 1/2 trial where we injected it

715
00:43:36.236 --> 00:43:37.256
intravitreously.

716
00:43:39.656 --> 00:43:40.336
And that worked

717
00:43:41.256 --> 00:43:44.096
reasonably well except that there was some vitritis.

718
00:43:44.456 --> 00:43:48.376
And you can imagine that that's got quite a large volume and so the drug

719
00:43:48.436 --> 00:43:51.676
was diluted. Then in the second set of trials, we actually did

720
00:43:51.696 --> 00:43:55.396
suprachoroidal right into the choroidal space so it can diffuse

721
00:43:55.836 --> 00:43:58.576
into the tumor, and then we shined the light on it.

722
00:43:58.886 --> 00:44:02.356
And we found no vitreous there. And so we decided to do a Phase III trial

723
00:44:03.296 --> 00:44:05.836
with suprachoroidal injection, and it's well underway.

724
00:44:05.876 --> 00:44:06.876
It should probably read out

725
00:44:07.756 --> 00:44:10.296
in a year, and it's only in about 100 patients.

726
00:44:10.716 --> 00:44:14.616
And the primary endpoint is both preservation of vision, and so far in the

727
00:44:14.636 --> 00:44:16.136
Phase II trials, we've had excellent

728
00:44:16.496 --> 00:44:20.276
preservation of vision, and

729
00:44:20.336 --> 00:44:23.816
also the delay to referral to standard of care

730
00:44:24.116 --> 00:44:27.426
versus no treatment, because these are small tumors and generally are followed by

731
00:44:27.516 --> 00:44:31.396
watchful waiting, but it often ends up that these metastasize before

732
00:44:31.416 --> 00:44:31.956
they're treated.

733
00:44:33.556 --> 00:44:34.576
I just keep hitting the wrong button.

734
00:44:35.596 --> 00:44:39.416
So this just shows the data from the Phase II trial, where there was no placebo

735
00:44:39.496 --> 00:44:43.296
control, but we compared what happened when we were doing the dose escalation,

736
00:44:43.696 --> 00:44:47.576
where there were actually subtherapeutic doses to what we now are using as

737
00:44:47.616 --> 00:44:51.436
a therapeutic dose in the clinical trials, which is

738
00:44:51.455 --> 00:44:54.216
three cycles of three weekly injections.

739
00:44:54.596 --> 00:44:58.536
And as you can see that the time to referral to standard of care

740
00:44:58.596 --> 00:45:00.576
is much greater in the therapeutic dose.

741
00:45:01.076 --> 00:45:04.886
And if you look at these tumors that are actively growing at the time of

742
00:45:04.916 --> 00:45:06.496
treating with the therapeutic dose,

743
00:45:07.396 --> 00:45:09.316
you can see that they basically stop growing.

744
00:45:12.296 --> 00:45:13.796
So the second

745
00:45:15.056 --> 00:45:18.696
cancer that we're going for now is non-muscle

746
00:45:18.736 --> 00:45:22.496
invasive bladder cancer, and that's in a Phase 1/2

747
00:45:22.516 --> 00:45:26.275
trial where we do local administration and light activation via

748
00:45:26.636 --> 00:45:30.476
a standard cystoscope. And I can tell you, the data's not been

749
00:45:30.516 --> 00:45:34.156
published, but it's been discussed, that in a study that was

750
00:45:34.316 --> 00:45:38.176
a window of opportunity where we would treat the

751
00:45:38.236 --> 00:45:38.756
patient

752
00:45:39.556 --> 00:45:41.136
and then two or three weeks later

753
00:45:42.976 --> 00:45:46.396
it would be taken out by standard surgery, there was no tumor left.

754
00:45:46.896 --> 00:45:50.616
Okay? So we're very optimistic that this is going to be also a successful

755
00:45:50.656 --> 00:45:52.576
treatment for bladder cancer.

756
00:45:54.976 --> 00:45:58.116
Okay. So thanks to our many collaborators. We talked about a few here.

757
00:45:58.796 --> 00:46:01.636
I don't have time to do it all, but obviously Doug and I don't do it.

758
00:46:02.336 --> 00:46:04.096
And thanks a lot for your attention and for

759
00:46:05.076 --> 00:46:05.776
being here today.
